<normalizedToken id="8D9281593EF40282C52129DF6DA54FC3" originalValue="Río">Rio</normalizedToken>
Coco, Nicaragua (Fig. 28).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C22A48BE45865F914E76B844610486A1" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="98155F3021DF58395B1879F4C1263F04" pageNumber="65">
Remarks. The list of objective synonyms highlights the uncertain generic affinities of the species. However, its relationship to 
<taxonomicName id="424551C7973CCD79739BAC66D332A459" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="65" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nematopus">H. nematopus</taxonomicName>
is supported not only by the present morphological study, but also by several recent molecular phylogenies (Martin &amp; Bermingham 1998; Hulsey et al. 2004; Concheiro 
<normalizedToken id="4C9500959C3662EF099C24C382FB121A" originalValue="Pérez">Perez</normalizedToken>
et al. 2007).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7311BE6A3C3BE058B1C531F9D8D1D23F" pageNumber="65">
The entire original description of 
<taxonomicName id="1BF4347612FF403122FB6920D3D5973E" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A9A8BE99-0308-4DF9-9916-9C3C02CC68D0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypsophrys unimaculatus Agassiz 1859:408" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="65" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="unimaculatus">H. unimaculatus Agassiz, 1859</taxonomicName>
from Lake Nicaragua gives no other detail but that it “resembles 
<taxonomicName id="895AA6B7C6E6D860AFD2993AADAEBEA7" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:EA7E8608-36C7-464B-90FF-AAC5CA4A23E9" authority="Quoy &amp; Gaimard, 1824" authorityName="Quoy &amp; Gaimard" authorityYear="1824" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sparidae" genus="Chrysophrys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Chrysophrys Quoy &amp; Gaimard 1824:299" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="65" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Chrysophrys</taxonomicName>
” (= 
<taxonomicName id="179F7640275749F42F23633DCCC5A94E" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:DF63CB60-585E-4200-8684-56A3E392011A" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sparidae" genus="Sparus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Sparus aurata Linnaeus 1758:277" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="65" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="aurata">Sparus aurata Linnaeus</taxonomicName>
), a Mediterranean and north Atlantic coastal fish (Eschmeyer 2005). Nevertheless, Kullander and Hartel (1997) explained how this simple statement leaves no doubt that the species involved is 
<taxonomicName id="1D7DFE50D411250288E63376E9E7B60D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="65" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nicaraguensis">H. nicaraguensis</taxonomicName>
(the only species in Lake Nicaragua to have an oval lateral blotch similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="42D4293C92646D885C3299432E64AC13" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:EA7E8608-36C7-464B-90FF-AAC5CA4A23E9" authority="Quoy &amp; Gaimard, 1824" authorityName="Quoy &amp; Gaimard" authorityYear="1824" class="Actinopterygii" family="Sparidae" genus="Chrysophrys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Chrysophrys Quoy &amp; Gaimard 1824:299" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="65" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Chrysophrys</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="632E5A38B56C6E6F73793A1B4F99A1D0" pageNumber="65">
Because there are no types of 
<taxonomicName id="50EF88E43E398798FBFADCEFECFCAD71" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A9A8BE99-0308-4DF9-9916-9C3C02CC68D0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hypsophrys unimaculatus Agassiz 1859:408" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="65" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="unimaculatus">H. unimaculatus</taxonomicName>
and the name constitutes a senior synonym unused after 1899 (ICZN 1999), I shall file a petition to ICZN to conserve the younger specific epithet 
<taxonomicName id="0E41ABB898EBE40AB55D4AD9B589EBEC" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cichlidae" genus="Hypsophrys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Perciformes" pageNumber="65" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nicaraguensis">nicaraguensis</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
